<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-227-612  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 227 612.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Feb 20 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>HongKong Telephone abandons new pay scales. (Hong Kong TelephoneCompany Ltd.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wingrove, Norman.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hong Kong Telephone Company Ltd. (salaries, etc.).andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsSalaryPersonnel ManagementPersonnel Problems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>HONGKONG TELEPHONE ABANDONS NEW PAY SCALES CAUSEWAY BAY, HONGKONG, 1990 FEB16 (NB) -- Hongkong Telephone (Telco) has postponed indefinitely plans tointroduce new pay scales which would, in theory at least, have resulted incuts for many junior employees.andM;Following protests from staff, some of whom actually stood to gain from thenew scales, Telco announced the decision to abandon recommendations ofconsultants Hay Management.andM;Telco management had been at pains to point out that the planned changes weresimply a rationalisation that would correct salaries that were over-generouscompared with those for comparable posts in other companies.andP;  The anomalieshad arisen from the widespread tendency in recent years for informationtechnology industry pay scales to rise to excessive levels as a result of thebrain drain now afflicting the colony.andP;  Telco maintained that under the newterms staff would actually be better off.andP;  Not only would those affected begaining in such areas as medical cover, they would have greater opportunitiesfor advancement with the abandonment of outdated rules governing jobdemarcation.andM;The staff were not to be persuaded, however, and the company eventuallybacked down until a better solution can be found.andM;The real issue was the natural reluctance of any worker to accept a cut insalary, however theoretical, versus the need of a company widely regarded asan enlightened employer to retreat from extravagant policies generated by theneed to keep workers.andP;  There is a widespread staff crisis in Hongkongbusiness, companies desperately trying to maintain staffing levels asqualified personnel emigrate with the approach of the 1997 hand-over toChina.andP;  Telco, it would seem, has been the victim of its own farsightednessin trying to forestall problems by offering inflated salaries in the last fewyears.andM;Hongkong Telephone is a company in Britain's Cable and Wireless PLC group,the world's largest telecommunications company.andM;(Norman Wingrove/19900217/Press Contact: Alice Yao, Hongkong Telecom, + 852529 8323)</TEXT></DOC>